Do not delete the Volume ID directly from Ceph CSI unless you have confirmed it is a stale operation. That error usually means the CSI controller has an in-memory lock, not that the volume itself is bad.

First check VolumeAttachment

oc get volumeattachment

Find the attachment for the PVC:

oc get volumeattachment -o yaml | grep -B10 -A20 20c6298b

or

oc get volumeattachment -o yaml | grep -B10 -A20 347c9448

If a VolumeAttachment is stuck and the pod is not using it, delete it:

oc delete volumeattachment <volumeattachment-name>


---

Most common fix: restart CSI pods

For RBD:

oc delete pod -n openshift-storage -l app=csi-rbdplugin
oc delete pod -n openshift-storage -l app=csi-rbdplugin-provisioner

For CephFS:

oc delete pod -n openshift-storage -l app=csi-cephfsplugin
oc delete pod -n openshift-storage -l app=csi-cephfsplugin-provisioner

The DaemonSet/Deployment recreates them automatically and clears the stuck operation.


---

Check if operation is stuck in Ceph

Enter toolbox:

oc rsh -n openshift-storage deploy/rook-ceph-tools

Check health:

ceph -s

Look for:

slow ops
blocked requests
MDS laggy

If present, the CSI operation may be waiting on Ceph.


---

If you really want to find the PVC from the Volume ID

oc get pv | grep 20c6298b

or

oc get pv -o yaml | grep -B20 -A20 20c6298b

Then identify the PV and PVC.


---

Before deleting anything, please share:

oc get volumeattachment
oc get pv | grep 20c6298b
oc get pods -n openshift-storage | grep csi
ceph -s

Deleting the wrong RBD image or CephFS volume is a one-way street, and you don't want to throw the baby out with the bathwater. The output will tell us whether this is a CSI lock, a stuck attachment, or a backend Ceph issue.
